 Expanding Universe Model

There was always something I couldn't wrap my head around in the expanding universe model.

According to the theory, the universe is expanding at a rapid rate and from any point in the universe everything is moving away from you. My main problem has always been, how can everything be moving away from you? What about the stuff behind you-- wouldn't that be moving towards you?

The answer is in a 3-dimensional model (for an 11 dimensional theory).

Basically you have a balloon covered in pennies. The pennies are like galaxies, each galaxy is held together (and does not move) by it's own gravity. As the universe expands, the balloon fills up and gets bigger, and you see that all the pennies move away from each other.

Also, based on this theory, all the planets SG-1 visits must not be in our galaxy. The gates in our galaxy have not changed position due to this shift, as the galaxy holds together on its own via gravity.

The only gates that have moved are those in other galaxies. Those are the ones adjusted for and the ones SG-1 visits.

If there were any other gates in our galaxy they would have been able to dial into them before the adjustment was made.

Does this make sense?

If a stargate was real, then this is how it would be implemented.

Each galaxy within the system would be divided up into 1987690320 sections. Each section would be assigned a stargate address.
However there are only a few thousand stargates in the galaxy, meaning that most of these sections don't have a stargate in them.
And the Ancients would have made sure that the chances of two stargates being in one section would be highly unlikely (Even though we saw this occur in Solitudes, we learned several things in later episodes, such as a dominating gates etc...)

Only one planet per solar system can usually have a stargate, as usually only one planet is within the appropriate ecosphere to support life. The solar systems within the galaxy move around, as the galaxy is a giant spiral that spins, growing stars in the middle, and spinning them outwards to the edges of it's arms.

It's hard for me to explain this on a real model such as the milky way... so let's use this small theoretical galaxy I have created called the "Silky Way":



The Silky Way stargate system has 16 possible stargate addresses. However the galaxy has only 3 stargates (as we discussed earlier, there are far more possible stargate addresses than there are stargates).
The stargates in this picture are highlited with a red dot.

Now due to planetary shift and the solar systems shifting around... after 5000 years in the Silky Way, the stargates would have moved into other sections of the system:




Hence the need to adjust the addresses for planetary shift. (Notice 2 of the stargates now must have adjusted addresses... however one of them still has it's old address like Abydos)

So the changing of stargate addresses really doesn't have to do with the galaxy moving, as the addresses for stargates are relative to the center of the galaxy. But they DO have to do with the solar systems moving around, so must continually be adjusted.
